        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/oew2B.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 303087,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 611819,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/611819/dnault",
                "reputation": 9068,
                "display_name": "dnault",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1614618641,
            "creation_date": 1406586416,
            "body": "<p>Propagate the checked exception as a RuntimeException:<\/p>\n<pre><code>try {\n    return someMethod(i);\n} catch (SomeException e) {\n    throw new RuntimeException(e);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>EDIT: Since the transformed list is lazily evaluated, the exception won't be thrown until you access the list elements. You can force the evaluation by copying the transformed list into a new list, like:<\/p>\n<pre><code>s = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(s);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>You could wrap that in a try-catch block that catches RuntimeException and handles it however you want; your original SomeException instance can be obtained by calling getCause() on the RuntimeException. Or you could just let the RuntimeException bubble up.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25005345,
            "question_id": 25005112,
            "last_edit_date": 1614618641
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/41db75c41287aa4e0f467cefeeb5fef3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 14964198,
                "user_type": "unregistered",
                "user_id": 10803015,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10803015/sheraud",
                "reputation": 11,
                "display_name": "sheraud"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1545076400,
            "creation_date": 1545076400,
            "body": "<p>You can use<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public interface FunctionWithException&lt;T, R, E extends Exception&gt; {\n    public R apply(T t) throws E;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 53822125,
            "question_id": 25005112
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcfbbb1f446ffe5cadbbeb893c53a5d1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 4701145,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3804677,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3804677/fabien-fleureau",
                "reputation": 693,
                "display_name": "Fabien Fleureau",
                "accept_rate": 40
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1424167104,
            "creation_date": 1406713524,
            "body": "<p>It depends on how you want to handle the exception.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Stop the list transformation when an exception occurs: See @dnault's answer. <\/li>\n<li><p>Continue the list transformation and remove the element which caused exception (and log some error message).\nIn this case, we will return null when an exception occurs, this null value will be removed from final list:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; s = Lists.newArrayList(\n                Iterables.filter(\n                Iterables.transform(l, new Function&lt;Integer, String&gt;() {\n                @Override\n                   public String apply(Integer i) {\n                     try {\n                        return someMethod(i);\n                    } catch (SomeException e) {\n                        e.printStackTrace();\n                        return null;\n                    }\n                   }\n     }), Predicates.notNull()))`\n<\/code><\/pre><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>EDIT\nIf someMethod can return null value then you should a wrapper like this one:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Wrapper {\n    public Exception exception = null;\n    public String result = null;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The list transformation will then be:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    List&lt;Wrapper&gt; wrappers = Lists.newArrayList(\n            Iterables.filter(\n            Iterables.transform(l, new Function&lt;Integer, Wrapper&gt;() {\n               @Override\n               public Wrapper apply(Integer i) {\n                  Wrapper wrapper = new Wrapper();\n                  try {\n                    wrapper.result = someMethod(i);\n                  } catch (SomeException e) {\n                    wrapper.exception = e;\n                  }\n                  return wrapper;\n                }\n             }), new Predicate&lt;Wrapper&gt;() {\n                @Override\n                public boolean apply(Wrapper wrapper) {\n                    return wrapper.exception == null;\n                }\n            }));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25033632,
            "question_id": 25005112,
            "last_edit_date": 1424167104
        }
